english:
  title: The Snow Mountain
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Snow Mountain lies in the Western Regions—a name I had merely heard, never knowing its true face. There was one called Ox-Chan who took this name for himself, following my words. The oxen upon Snow Mountain grow sleekest and most radiant; their purity is especially remarkable, so much so that even their dung serves the temple's precept platforms. I once heard this told in his writings and ventured to share it; since the Master already knew of such things, he was pleased to accept it. Now that he seeks my words, I find myself unable to demur.

    The Analects teaches: "In painting, the white ground comes last." Whiteness means a surface without ornament—yet it receives all five colors perfectly. So too with nature: it rests still and unmoved, pure and singular, free of mixture, embodying the fullness of the Five Virtues. Nature is what I must cultivate, and in this, neither the Confucian nor the Buddhist differs in the slightest.

    Ox-Chan through Precept cuts away the defilements of desire that would soil his whiteness, through Meditation guards against the turbulence of desire that would cloud his clarity, through Wisdom transforms desire until it returns to its original purity. Then purity dwells not in the ox, but in myself.

    When I face the Master, I stand as though within Snow Mountain itself—and Snow Mountain is not far. The Master takes Snow Mountain as his emblem; thus Snow Mountain and Master are not two. Through Precept he enters Meditation, through Meditation awakens Wisdom, and the whole body with its perfect functioning becomes purely white and clear—equal to the Buddha himself. What more is there to doubt? The Snow Mountain's true face dwells in the Master. It dwells in the Master.
  footnotes:
    - 'Ox-Chan (牛禪): A Buddhist name combining ''ox'' with the character for meditation/Chan Buddhism, suggesting a practitioner who embodies the patient strength of an ox.'
    - 'The Five Virtues (五常): Fundamental Confucian virtues—benevolence, righteousness, propriety, wisdom, and trustworthiness.'
    - This prose poem synthesizes Buddhist and Confucian teachings, using the Snow Mountain as a metaphor for the cultivated mind of the Master.
